Ecology . Intertidal and shallow subtidal, probably to at least 5 m ; rocky and mixed sand-rock bottoms, under rocks and in rock crevices, apparently capable of boring tunnels into hard rocks using its major cheliped (
Ricaurte et al. 1995
); also in estuaries and mangroves, under rocks or debris in muddy sand or mud, sometimes in or under perforated chunks of wood (e.g., specimens from Chame Bay and Coiba in present study); usually encountered in male-female pairs; feeds mostly on algae growing on burrow walls (
Ricaurte et al. 1995
).
